There seem to be two leading views of globalization: either that it is done and the world is flat (a view popularized by Tom Friedman) or that it has led to a world dominated by corporations (Naomi Klein). Pankaj Ghemawat disagrees with both -- and his case, backed by data, can be convincing. His most recent book, World 3.0, based on extensive research and backed up with abundant data, explores the true face of globalization--and shows that the world is not one vast market, but many small, interconnected, discrete entities, with varying degrees of openness to one another. That even the most open economies are still relatively closed. That we live in a world of semi-globalization at best. Ghemawat also refutes the assumption that globalization leads to homogeneization. According to The Economist, World 3.0 “should be read by anyone who wants to understand the most important economic development of our time.”

Ghemawat is a professor of strategic management at IESE Business School in Spain. In his latest work, he explores another kind of networked economy--the cross-border "geography" of Facebook and Twitter followers.

author: Pankaj_Ghemawat;
title: Actually, the world isn't flat

aws-transcripts.transcript: I'm here to talk to you about how globalized we are, how globalized we aren't and why it's important toe actually be accurate in making those kinds of assessments. And the leading point of view on this weather, measured by number of books, sold. Mentions in media or surveys that I've run with groups ranging from my students to delegates to the World Trade Organization is this view that national borders really don't matter very much anymore. Cross border integration is closed to complete, and we live in one world. And what's interesting about this view is again it's a view that's held by pro globalize ER's like Tom Friedman, from whose book this quote is obviously excerpted. But it's also helped by anti globalized who see this giant globalization tsunami that's about to wreck all our lives if it hasn't already done so. The other thing, I would add is that this is not a new view. I'm a little bit of an amateur historian, So I spent some time going back trying to see the first mention of this kind of thing. And the best earliest quote that I could find was one from David Livingston, writing in the 18 fifties about how the railroad, the Steamship and the telegraph were integrating East Africa perfectly with the rest of the world. Now, clearly, David Livingston was a little bit ahead of his time. But it does seem useful to ask ourselves just how global are we before we think about where we go from here. So the best way I found of trying to get people to take seriously the idea that the world may not be flat may not even be close to flat is with some data.
